issues.description: The problem statement requires that each class constructor takes all attributes in the same order as they appear in the UML (first attribute on top => first parameter). For ExcellenceLand the UML lists excellencyLevel (double) then excellentEnough (boolean) (and the task text additionally requires a private List<Ride> rides attribute). Therefore the expected constructor parameter order is (double excellencyLevel, boolean excellentEnough, List<Ride> rides) (or at least that excellencyLevel should appear before excellentEnough). The solution implementation provides a constructor with the parameter order (List<Ride> rides, boolean excellentEnough, double excellencyLevel), which reverses the intended order and places rides first. This contradicts the explicit constructor-order requirement and will confuse students about the expected parameter order and cause signature/test mismatches.
issues.suggested_fix: Make the ExcellenceLand constructor parameter order match the UML/requirement: declare the constructor as public ExcellenceLand(double excellencyLevel, boolean excellentEnough, List<Ride> rides) (or place excellencyLevel before excellentEnough), and assign parameters to the corresponding fields. Update the template/solution so the constructor signature matches the problem statement; alternatively, if rides is intentionally first, update the problem statement to explicitly specify that ordering.
